irca 1148","abt. 1150":"circa 1150","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","1129":"1129","ABT 1174":"circa 1174","1126":"1126","1214":"1214","1148":"1148","Abt 1168":"circa 1168","1168":"1168","ABT 1200":"circa 1200","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","ABT 1182":"circa 1182","Crawford, Lanark, Scotland":"Crawford, Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ercildoun, Scotland":"Ercildoun, East Fallowfield Township, Chester, Pennsylvania, Verenigde Staten van Amerika","Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Crawford, Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT 1148–ABT 1200":"about 1148–about 1200","1148–1200":"1148–1200","1144–Female":"1144–Deceased","1150–1214":"1150–1214","1182–Male":"1182–Deceased","1129–1168":"1129–1168","1126–Female":"1126–Deceased","ABT 1147":"about 1147","ABT 1148":"about 1148","abt. 1150":"about 1150","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","1129":"1129","ABT 1174":"about 1174","1126":"1126","1214":"1214","1148":"1148","Abt 1168":"about 1168","1168":"1168","ABT 1200":"about 1200","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","ABT 1182":"about 1182","Crawford, Lanark, Scotland":"Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ercildoun, Scotland":"Ercildoun, East Fallowfield Township, Chester, Pennsylvania, United States","Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lindsay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Lindsey in Lincolnshire, England. This is first found in the form <i>Lindissi</i>, apparently a derivative of the British name of   Lincoln  . To this was later added the Old English element <i>ēg</i> ‘island’, since the place was virtually cut off by the surrounding fenland. The surname was taken to Scotland at an early date and is the name of an important and powerful Scottish family.","Irish: adopted as an equivalent ofvarious Gaelic names (see   Lindsey  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Linzy","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish, Irish, or English   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  . Compare   Lenzy  ."]},{"name":"Linzey","meanings":["English: variant of   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  ."]},{"name":"Lindsey","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lindsay  .","Irish: shortened and Anglicized form of various Gaelic surnames, as for example <b>Ó Loingsigh</b> (see   Lynch   1), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntóg</b> (see   McClintock  ), and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn   and   Lynn  )."]},{"name":"Lincoln","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city of Lincoln, so named from an original British name <i>Lindo-</i> ‘lake’ + Latin <i>colonia</i> ‘settlement, colony’. The place was an important administrative center during the Roman occupation of Britain and in the Middle Ages it was a center for the manufacture of cloth, including the famous ‘Lincoln green’.","African American: adoption of the surname in 1 above, in honor of Abraham Lincoln, the 16th president of the US, who abolished slavery.","History: Abraham Lincoln (1809–65), 16th president of the US, was the son of an illiterate laborer, descended from Samuel Lincoln, who had emigrated from England to MA in 1637."]},{"name":"Linsey","meanings":["Scottish, Irish, or English: variant of   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  .","Americanized form of German   Linse   or Swiss German <b>Linsi</b>, see   Lins  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Lindsay was born about 1148, in Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Walter de Lindsay, was 21 and his mother, Lindsay Mrs., was 24. He married Alienora De Limesi Of Crawford about 1174, in Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1200, at the age of 54."},"et":{"ABT 1148–ABT 1200":"umbes 1148–umbes 1200","1148–1200":"1148–1200","1144–Female":"1144–Surnud","1150–1214":"1150–1214","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1129–1168":"1129–1168","1126–Female":"1126–Surnud","ABT 1147":"umbes 1147","ABT 1148":"umbes 1148","abt. 1150":"umbes 1150","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","1129":"1129","ABT 1174":"umbes 1174","1126":"1126","1214":"1214","1148":"1148","Abt 1168":"umbes 1168","1168":"1168","ABT 1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","ABT 1182":"umbes 1182","Crawford, Lanark, Scotland":"Crawford, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Ercildoun, Scotland":"Ercildoun, East Fallowfield Township, Chester, Pennsylvania, Ameerika Ühendriigid","Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Crawford, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1148–ABT 1200":"noin 1148–no